content:
Yes, it's possible to achieve an infinite background effect without using an image, just by setting a background color and using CSS gradients.

Here's an example:
```css
body {
  background: linear-gradient(to bottom, #e8e8e8 0%, #e8e8e8 80%, #fff 80%, #fff 100%);
  background-size: 100% 100vh;
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
}
```
In this example, we're using a linear gradient as the background, which transitions from `#e8e8e8` to `#fff`. The `background-size` property is set to `100% 100vh` so that the gradient covers the entire width of the viewport and is repeated vertically every `100vh` (i.e., every full viewport height).

The trick to make the background appear infinite is by defining a "stop" in the gradient at `80%` of the height, where the color changes from `#e8e8e8` to `#fff`. This creates the illusion that the background color extends infinitely downward beyond the actual height of the page.

You can adjust the colors and the position of the stop to achieve the desired effect.
